INJURY PREVENTION (What Wrestlers Do)
Training Regimens:
Year-Round Maintenance:

Strength Training (3-4x/week)

Focus on injury-prone areas: neck, shoulders, knees, back
Functional movements, not bodybuilding
Flexibility/Mobility (daily)

Yoga, stretching
Prevents muscle strains
Cardiovascular (4-5x/week)

Keeps weight down (less stress on joints)
Endurance for long matches
Recovery

Massage therapy (weekly)
Cryotherapy, ice baths
Sleep (8+ hours crucial)
Nutrition (anti-inflammatory diet)
Ring Awareness

Working with safe workers
Communication in matches
Protecting yourself and opponent
AEW/WWE Support Systems:
Medical Staff:

Doctors on-site at TV tapings
Physical therapists travel with roster
Referral network to specialists in every city
Wellness Programs:

Regular check-ups
Injury prevention education
Mental health resources
Insurance:

Comprehensive coverage for surgeries, PT
Some companies cover rehab fully
Financial:

Many contracts guarantee pay during injury
Tyler's contract had downside guarantee (kept getting paid)
KEY TAKEAWAYS
✅ Injuries are inevitable in wrestling - high-impact, year-round schedule

✅ Recovery is SLOW - rushing back leads to re-injury

✅ Mental health matters - psychological toll often worse than physical

✅ Creative flexibility crucial - companies must adapt storylines to real injuries

✅ Support systems essential - wrestlers need medical, financial, emotional support

✅ Communication is key - between wrestler, doctors, company, fans

✅ Returns are uncertain - some come back 100%, some retire, some struggle